      "writtenOn": "2015-09-29T15:52:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "nit: don\u0027t use \u0027echo\u0027, because it doesn\u0027t deal with parameters which begin with a dash cleanly. A better alternative is to use \u0027printf %s \"....\"\u0027 instead.\n\nHowever, in this case, there is no reason to use echo or printf at all, just call the command, and redirect stderr just in case, as in:\n\n  git_repo_get_head () {\n    git -C \"$1\" rev-parse --short HEAD 2\u003e/dev/null\n  }\n\nNote that directory paths should be escaped, in case they contain spaces. As a special exception, mandated by Posix, you don\u0027t need to escape the value in simple assignments, as in:\n\n    BAR\u003d\"hello world\"\n    FOO\u003d$BAR                  # sets \u0027FOO\u0027 to \"hello world\"\n\nHowever, this doesn\u0027t apply if there is anything before the assignment, including an \u0027eval\u0027. Yes, shell scripting is weird.",
      "revId": "5991852c154b495aa706fa25f40f9dc2f50720a3",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
